comments.text: Hey there - sorry for the delay in getting back to you. I'm probably the one who put the review up on Hobbyking. That stub is really a hole (as seen from the outside) that acts as a hinge point opposite the drive shaft. Some robotics applications use this mounting method. It does not affect the "sturdiness" of the servo. They are good, strong servos but the problem I was having with them was that the shafts that hold the metal gears are held in place with plastic, so ultimately the plastic breaks and the gears separate. However, I was pushing the limits of the servos and also exposing them to some "shock" on the output shaft, so they might work out fine for your application. Cheers!

description.text:
The first 3D shape shows a cross section of a dipper that uses air pressure to hold water. Holding the knob on top between your index and middle finger, submerse the container in water. Then plug the hole in the knob with your thumb and lift the dipper out of the water. Water will stay in the container until you remove your thumb.
The project is to explain the physics involved and make a design based on them to demonstrate how they work.
This was designed in FreeCAD using only basic primitives.

Objectives: This is an introduction to CAD learning boolean operations on primitives to make more complex shapes. Also to learn basic physics of atmosphere, gas and pressure. Audiences: This project could be a part of teaching the physics of atmosphere, gas and pressure. Preparation: A basic understanding of primitives, position, and boolean operations. Also a basic understanding of the physics of pressure. It is a simple design that should be easy to make in any design program of the instructors choice. Steps: First design the outer shape as a solid, combining cones and cylinders. Then make a similar, smaller core inside the outer shape. I have copied the core outside the solid shape as an illustration in one of the pictures. Then subtract the core from the solid shape, leaving about 2mm walls. Finally use the "Fillet" tool to make the edges nice and round. Remember to use the "Fillet" tool on the core also, or the walls may be cut to thin. Use the "cross section" tool to check the walls before printing. Also make sure you don't have to much overhang or you will have to use supports. 45 degrees should be safe. Results: Innovative designs based on the physical principles should of course be rewarded. I would say the important design consideration are overhang to avoid support structures, at least internally, matching the core to the surface so the walls have consistent thickness, and ergonomics. Also a better understanding of the physics of pressure.

title: Prusa Z motor mount and Coupling

description.text:
A revised Z motor mount with thrust bearing and coupling.
I didn't like the idea of the weight of the x-axis pulling down on the motor shaft and the possibility of the coupling slipping (although nopheads redesign has worked perfectly).
With this design all the weight is on the thrust bearing not the motor, and so far the threaded bar has run perfectly true giving some very nice prints.
The thrust bearing I found quite easily on ebay at Â£7.00 for 4, and have an 8mm ID and a 16mm OD.

1) Cut a 8mm threaded bar to 280mm the standard one is too short.
2) Fix a single nut to one end of the bar so it cannot turn, I drilled a 3mm hole through the nut and bar then inserted a roll pin and cut to length.
3) Fit the coupling to the motor with the 3mm nut and bolt and make sure it is a nice easy fit over the 8mm nut but with no play.
4) Insert the bearing and threaded bar then use 4 x M3 screws to fix the motor to the holder or if you have very long M3 bolts it can be bolted through the Z-motor mount although I didn't have any bolts long enough to try this.
4) Place the bearing holder in the Z motor mount and screw into the x-end.
5)True the axis back up and you are ready to go (I hope ;-) )

comments.text: I have blatantly copied your thing, take a look at thing 102490, I liked your design but wanted to use a single beam coupling to mitigate alignment issues, these couplings should not be used in situations where they can be stretched, so your solution to support a thrust bearing to carry the weight of the x-axis was ideal.  I thought I would try some cleaver "plastic" bearings, these also compensate for miss-alignment so work well with the beam coupling, works a treat and no wear issues so far.

A model of a TARDIS, designed so as to make it easy to split & print as coasters.
Each piece is labelled as "top", "middle" or "bottom" to help you figure out where they fit together.  "A" pieces go lower than "B", etc.  The "x2" or "x5" or whatever indicates how many times to print that piece.  In the end, you should have 27 pieces - not the roundest number, but it's what was needed to get everything to both look good and line up properly.
There are 2 versions of the 12 "panel" pieces because not all cups/mugs fit into holes on coasters.  I recommend printing the "no hole" set for these so that you have 12 coasters to use with oversized mugs.
NOTE: I have NOT printed a full set of these myself, because I am nearly certain that I'm going to run out of the irreplaceable blue that I began the project with, and I don't really have the funds to start again right now.  But I have printed enough of them that I know they fit together and it should be really cool when it's done, so I wanted to share now rather than later.

Notes: I have trouble on my printer with top layers on high resolution (I need ~10 layers just to cover all the gaps), but that seems to be every model I ever print, so I assume it's just my printer. These really don't need high resolution to look good (in fact, my low pieces actually look better for the reason mentioned above), but high ends up using less filament in the end, so I recommend using it anyway - this uses a LOT of filament.

Felt Bottoms You're going to want to buy some felt or something to act as "feet" so the plastic doesn't ruin your table. The holes on the top of each coaster are designed to hold the feet of the coaster above, although they are very small. You'll want to line them up so that they are just covering the guides (the little holes on the bottom of each coaster) on the outer edge; excess felt goes toward the center. If you do this right, the coasters should stack properly with little effort. I got x75 3/8" "medium duty felt pads" at a local hardware store for $3, and then cut them into quarters to fit in the holes. They seem to be working just right.

Test piece with 0.5mm thick circular base and 0.5mm thick 1mm wide circles with 1mm gaps. For testing printer behaviour.

Issues that can be identified by printing this:
  • Ability to cleanly print a lot of segments per second. Each ring is made of 240 segments, so the count per second increases from outer to inner circles.
    â€“ Backlash issues. The rings are normally formatted into two counter-rotating tracks, so that any backlash effect shows up as varying gap between the tracks.
    â€“ Extruder spillage. The printer should change direction and layer at the same point when printing the circles, and when printing fast with no extruder advance (which is available in at least the Marlin firmware), extra plastic is left at the direction/layer change spot.

description.text:
I know I know, the last thing Thingiverse needs is another phone case, but this is more about sharing an idea than offering anything to download, such is the true personal nature of this thing. My daughter Lauren, went round her friendship group and asked them to write down their tag on a piece of paper. A bit of graphics manipulation later and a conversion into .dxf cad file I was able to deboss these into a truly personalised phone case for her. For that special one off gift, I hope this inspires others to make something like this too. http://www.gyrobot.co.uk
http://www.facebook.com/gyrobotuk

Workfow :
1 . Scan the image by taking a picture of it.
  • Use Gimp/Photshop etc to manipulate the image into monochrome b/w.
  • Create the cad profile .dxf by using this free image to cad software from http://www.img2cad.com/
  • Import the .dxf file into your favorite CAD package to create the deboss.
    • I have not included the actual personalised case for the reason that I do not want it printed by anyone else (why should they want to?) and afterall, it is meant to be unique. I have however uploaded a free iPhone 4 for the first million downloaders. I printed the case with only a single perimeter around the infill, this gave the best definition for the lettering.

title: Delta-Six V-slot Magnetic arm carriage, effector and parts

description.text:
• These are my custom designed parts for the openbuilds Delta-Six printer project

  • The custom.zip contains all 123D Design files for customization and adaptation.

    carriage/effector designed for use with v-slot full v-wheels, and threaded steel balls for magnetic arms. The spacing of the steel balls is ~48.15mm. The screw caps are countersunk so they do not interfere with the magnetic arms.

    Led lights use generic led strips with adhesive backs. I have them wired directly into the power supply so they are always on. Makes for high visibility on your prints.

• Prints in multiple parts for wider use

    Designed for use with the e3dv6 (also works great with the volcano!), however the nozzle mount is printed separately so it should be fairly simple to adapt it for other nozzles. The fans are held on with m3 bolts/nuts. This allows them to swivel around instead of breaking when there's a print failure that causes the effector to pop off the magnetic joints. Also allows you to point them wherever is needed for different prints.

    Effector uses the large inductive sensor from amazon, this sensor is needed to add rigidity to the effector. The sensor is powerful enough to detect the aluminum through the borosilicate glass.

• I was inspired by step clamps used on CNC machines. this gives fantastic clearance.

  • I'm using the SeeMeCNC rostock heated bed with an aluminum sheet under the glass.

    In the zip there is another version using threaded bold and giant printed thumb screw. Was a really fun thing to model and see in use, however, because I have my nozzle as high up in the effector as possible (to minimize errors due to the angle of the effector) it limited my printable area.

• This is an experimentation, I was too lazy to go with a full flying extruder. but it works great!

    The extruder is suspended by some elastic bungees. I ordered a few types and picked the one that worked best. This allows the bowden tube to be as straight as possible for the majority of the print, and it greatly shortens the length of the tube.

• Delta-Six Project OpenBuilds Link
  • Inductive sensor Amazon Link
  • Threaded steel balls DeltaPrintr Link
  • Layer fans and heated bed SeeMeCNC
• Nozzle mount V2 updated the mount to hold e3d hotends much better. It takes a little bit of patience to get the nozzle into the mount, but once secured there is no wiggle at all.

description.text: Update - Here's the 2015 update for this project - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:688566 Back in December I found a great mod where someone shoved an SNES into a pelican case. I wanted to recreate this, but using a Raspberry Pi for a portable gaming rig. It took about 7 months of frustration, joy, anger, blood, fried boards, and tears but it is finally complete. This wouldn't have been possible without the awesome work people have put into the Retro Pie and Emulation Station projects. http://blog.petrockblock.com/retropie/ Here's a great walkthrough from Lifehacker - http://lifehacker.com/how-to-turn-your-raspberry-pi-into-a-retro-game-console-498561192 You can attempt to recreate my project, but I'd recommend using it as a template and make it your own. I've included the blank pieces that should fit the interior of the pelican case so you can modify it to you heart's content. I've left off the accent pieces that I printed in white. They helped hide the seams of the separate prints it took to put the faceplates together. The entire thing is waterproof and probably weighs 3 or 4 lbs. It probably wouldn't make you super popular with airport security, but the whole thing is portable. I've got a 16gb SD card for the main operating system and a 16gb flash drive for extra storage. It can boot into Raspbian and features wifi so you can ftp into it if wanted. Unfortunately there is no way to externally power the system while you are using it, but they are beefy lipo batteries that should hold out for several hours. I was able to get about 7 hours while plugged into an external HDMI TV with the internal screen powered off. If you were to play it using the internal screen, it would most likely last for 3ish hours. I'll post as many of the parts as I can find, but good luck and godspeed!

This is my entry for the Birdhouse Challenge â€“ a Birdhouse in the style of a Black Forest Cuckoo Clock!
